In [2]:
### Importing the CV and matplotlib library

import cv2

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
In [4]:
# Load image by passing the filepath/name of the image to the imread() 
gvn_image = cv2.imread("Dahlia.jpg")

# Change the color code of the given image to RGB format using the cvtColor() function
gvn_image = cv2.cvtColor(gvn_image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

# Plot the given original image using the imshow() function
plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
plt.imshow(gvn_image)
plt.axis("off")
plt.title("Original Image")
plt.show()
In [5]:
# to convert the given image to grayscale image
grayscle_image = cv2.cvtColor(gvn_image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)

# Plot the above Grayscale image for the given image using the imshow() function
plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
plt.imshow(grayscle_image, cmap="gray")
plt.axis("off")
plt.title("Grayscale Image")
plt.show()
In [7]:
# Get the inverted image by passing the above grayscale image as an argument to the bitwise_not() function
invertd_image = cv2.bitwise_not(grayscle_image)

#  Plot the Inverted Image
plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
plt.imshow(invertd_image, cmap="gray")
plt.axis("off")
plt.title("Inverted Image")
plt.show()
In [13]:
# Get the Smoothened image from the above inverted image using the GaussianBlur() function
smooth_image = cv2.GaussianBlur(invertd_image, (111, 111),sigmaX=0, sigmaY=0)

# Plot the Smoothed Image
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.imshow(smooth_image, cmap="gray")
plt.axis("off")
plt.title("Smoothened Image using GaussianBlur() function")
plt.show()
In [16]:
## Get the Pencil sketch from the above smoothened Image using divide method of CV library .
pencil_skecth = cv2.divide(grayscle_image, 255 - smooth_image, scale=256)

## Save the sketch . 
cv2.imwrite('sketch.png', pencil_skecth)

### Using cvtColor method of openCV for better clarity .
rgb_sketch=cv2.cvtColor(pencil_skecth, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

#plot the pencil Sketch
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.imshow(rgb_sketch,cmap='gray')
plt.axis("off")
plt.title("Output Pencil Sketch Image")
plt.show()
